CIPK OVC Key Performance Indicators (KPIs)

Presented by Roy Mwavita

Updated on 21_01_2025

Introduction

This report covers the key performance indicators (KPIs) for the USAID TUJITEGEMEE Project.


Objectives of the KPIs:

  • To evaluate the impact of the project on the targeted communities.

  • To identify gaps in service delivery and areas for improvement.

  • To track progress against set targets.

COP Target

The COP targets are the Presidents Emergency Plan for AIDS Relief (PEPFAR) Country Operational Plan (2022, 2023, 2024, etc.) targets.

These targets often involve indicators that measure key aspects of HIV prevention, treatment, and care, aiming to reduce the burden of HIV and improve health outcomes.

For USAID TUJITEGEMEE project, the indicators are as follows:

  • OVC_SERV

  • OVC_HIVSTAT

In addition to these core indicators, the project also tracks a range of other key performance indicators that contribute to the overall measurement of the programs impact.

These additional indicators provide a comprehensive view of the projects effectiveness, including its reach, quality of services, and the improvements made in the lives of vulnerable populations.

PEPFAR Monitoring: Going from Process to Impact

The overall goal of Orphans and Vulnerable (OVC) programming is to build the resiliency of families and children affected by HIV and AIDS so that they can meet their health, economic, education, and social development needs.

    Sinovuyo Preventive Program

    The Sinovuyo Program is an evidence-informed, 14-week parenting programme.

    Teens (both boys and girls) between 10-14 years and not enrolled in a comprehensive program are considered eligible for Sinovuyo program.

    The Programme specifically aims to:

  • Increase parenting knowledge, skill and confidence
  • Improve positive parenting behavior
  • Decrease harsh discipline
  • Increase teenagers self confidence
  • Increase teenagers sense of responsibility
  • Improve mental health and social support (both teenagers and parents)
  • Improve problem solving and communication skills (both teenagers and parents)

    CBIM Preventive Program



    Coaching Boys Into Men (CBIM) is an evidence-based violence prevention program that trains and motivates high school coaches to teach their young male athletes in:

    • healthy relationship skills,

    • mental health practices,

    • and that violence never equals strength through 12 weekly discussions in what is called the card series.

    Case Plan Achievement

    Case plan achievement is a key component of the USAID TUJITEGEMEE project, focusing on supporting OVC and households through individualized goals to improve health, education, and economic outcomes.

    Households and OVC can be graduated out of the program once they meet specific criteria, such as improved health, school retention, and economic stability.

    Graduation signifies the success of interventions and the long-term sustainability of outcomes, empowering beneficiaries to thrive independently and reducing their dependency on external support.

    Graphical Presentation of Comprehensive_SERV

    OVC_SERV

    • The goal of OVC programs is to build stability and resiliency in children and families who are exposed, living with, at risk of, or affected by HIV/AIDS. This is achieved through rigorous case management and provision of and access to health and socio-economic interventions.

    • Therefore, OVC_SERV is a direct (output) measure of the number of individuals receiving PEPFAR OVC program services for children and families affected by HIV/AIDS across the 3 program models. (MER 2.8, pg 50)

    How to calculate data for semi-annual results for OVC_SERV

    OVC_HIVSTAT

    • This is an indicator described as the percentage of orphans and vulnerable children (<18 years old and 18-20 years old) enrolled in the OVC Comprehensive program with HIV status reported to implementing partner.

    • The goal of monitoring OVC_HIVSTAT is to increase the proportion of children reported as active or graduated under OVC_SERV under age 18 with a known HIV status or for whom an HIV test is not required based on a risk assessment.

    How to Calculate OVC_HIVSTAT

    Important to NOTE:

    • The OVC_HIVSTAT Total Numerator should equal the OVC_SERV 0-20 years of age OVC Comprehensive age disaggregates, including active and graduated.

    • Under the OVC_HIVSTAT definition, only participants enrolled in the OVC Comprehensive program should have their HIV status reported.

    • Participants reported under the DREAMS or OVC Preventive OVC_SERV disaggregates should NOT be captured under OVC_HIVSTAT since the participants counted here are not enrolled in the OVC Comprehensive program.

    CPARA, Case Plan & Services Layering

    Case plan layering, in simple terms, is a case management process of addressing the needs of Orphans and Vulnerable Children (OVC) and their households by identifying gaps across various domainshealthy, stable, safe, and schooledand providing interventions accordingly.

    Case plan layering ensures that services provided are tracked and evaluated against the identified needs.

    High Viral Load Trend (Across Years)

    This slide aims to illustrate the temporal changes in the number of individuals with viral loads exceeding 200 copies per milliliter since 2022.

    By examining the data across different years, the slide provides insights into whether the incidence of high viral loads is increasing, decreasing, or remaining stable.

    Distribution of the Persistence of Unsuppressed Cases

    This slide aims to illustrate the variation in the duration that individuals with unsuppressed HIV viral loads remain in this state over time.

    By analyzing this distribution, the slide seeks to identify patterns or factors that contribute to prolonged periods of unsuppressed viral loads among patients. The analysis categorizes individuals based on their persistence in an unsuppressed state:

    • High Persistence: Individuals who remained unsuppressed across all five years, indicating significant challenges in achieving viral suppression.

    • Moderate Persistence: Individuals who remained unsuppressed in four out of five years.

    • Low Persistence Individuals who remained unsuppressed in only three of the five years, indicating low progress in sustaining viral suppression.

    • Minimal Persistence: Individuals who remained unsuppressed for just two years, highlighting fair progress in managing viral loads.

    • No Persistence: Individuals who were unsuppressed for under one year, highlighting high progress in managing viral loads.

    Understanding these categories provides valuable insights into the effectiveness of interventions and identifies areas for targeted support to improve long-term viral suppression outcomes.

    Effectiveness of Interventions in Achieving Viral Load Suppression

    1. Single vs.Multiple Interventions and Their Impact on Suppression Status

    This slide explores the correlation between the number of interventions providedsingle versus multiple interventionsand the suppression status (suppressed vs.unsuppressed) of OVCs.

    By examining how the combination of interventions influences viral suppression, the slide aims to identify whether multiple interventions are more effective than single interventions in helping OVCs achieve viral load suppression.

    2. Effectiveness of Interventions Based on Suppression Status

    This slide presents a visual summary of the effectiveness of different interventions based on the viral suppression status of OVCs.

    • The chart provides insights into how the different interventions contribute to viral load suppression.

    • The expected outcome of this slide is to highlight the effectiveness of various interventions in improving viral load suppression among OVCs.

    • By visualizing the distribution of suppressed versus unsuppressed cases for each intervention, we can identify which interventions are most successful in achieving suppression.

    Adolescent OVC Transition Planning

    Transition planning is theprocess of preparing an adolescent OVC to move from active participation in a given OVC program. Transition is appropriate when an adolescent OVC is on the verge of ageing out of a program.

    However, to provide for a buffer period for the planning and implementation of appropriate transition strategies, the project will identify and target adolescent OVC above 15 years, but below 18 years, with interventions based on their needs, that will support them to responsibly transition from receiving OVC assistance.

    Relevant Tools:

    • Transition readiness assessment checklist (TRAC)

    The checklist will help the case manager to assess the situation the OVC and their caregiver are in, and identify the needs of the adolescent, to inform the appropriate interventions/services that will support their transition goal(s).

    • Case plan template

    Based on the findings from the TRAC, the case plan template will be used to document the identified needs or gaps, as well as priority actions to address them.

    [source: SOP for Adolescent OVC Transition Planning]

    Impact of Interventions on Household Resilience: Tracking Benchmark Score Changes

    This slide highlights the impact of interventions on household resilience by tracking changes in benchmark scores over time.

    It examines how interventions provided to the household have influenced households progress, providing insights into whether these interventions have led to improvements or setbacks in resilience scores.

    The analysis categorizes households based on their score changes, offering a clear view of the effectiveness of the interventions in enhancing household resilience.

    A total of 185 households were provided interventions and tracked until the most recent update.

    This table summarizes the outcomes for the households:

    • Positive Change: Out of the 87 households, 47 of them showed a positive change in their outcomes.

    • No Change: 77 households, representing 42, experienced no change in their outcomes.

    • Negative Change: 21 households, representing 11, showed a negative change in their outcomes.

    This analysis provides insights into how the interventions have impacted the tracked households, including the number and percentage of positive, no, and negative changes.
